Holds the hundreds of stocks I keep in my evaluation radar.   Many are not worth too much of my time.  This worksheet uses the [[Spreadsheet Color Conventions]]

!!! The Fields

*''symbol'':  equity, and etfs, no funds. 
* ''how'': did I find out about it.  
*''updated'': when i last looked up the //analyst// and //div//idend fields, explained below
*''sectorName'': may even be a sub-sector for the symbol looked up in Fidelity, Google, Yahoo financial. see //secN// field
*''name'': how the world sees the company
*''risk:''  the Motley Fool risk assessment, lower is better.  I'm working on importing the working data on just the stocks we are both following, i.e. just because it's on their radar doesn't mean it's on this list.
*''Foolish'': for those rated by Motley Fool, what to they call it, //starter, new, now, best, hold...//
*''analyst'': the Fidelity composite analyst rating, 0 to 10 (the best), from a pool of 3rd party contributors.   This is not a live update, but the active rating on the //updated// day.  See the discussion below
*''div'': the latest dividend reported on the //updated// day
*''shares'': rounded number of shares
*''secN'': looked up in yet another table where I do the best I can to map the //sectorName// onto the CalandrosTable fields
* ''action'': LOOK, HOLD, BUY, SELL.
* //red line//
* //un-named//: links to a Yahoo Chart on the //symbol//
*''act on'': //symbo// receving //action//
*''to hold'' (2 columns): second column is uniqued list of symbols to //act on//
*''HOLD'', 5: number of shares held either by pat or myself.  next column is either ''p'' or ''m'' 
*''SORT'': sum of evaluation columns
* ''8,4,2,1,0'': evaluation, respectively of //analyst//, //div// threshold, //Fool// has a rating, and do we //Hold// it
*??: room for expansion
* ''A{B,C,D}'': collect, unique, and sort the //sector//,//action//,//symbol//

My first mention of Robert Bly's Iron John was on [[Monday, the 17th,|2019-06-17, Monday]] when I picked up the book for the first time in -- what? -- 25 years.   

I"ll be sharing this with the Bloomfield McGowan's in the person of Laurie Kessler.   Maybe more later.   But first, here is a cute story from the chapter: Riding the Red, the White, and the Black Horse.   Later a bit of a synopsis of the meaning of the colors and the order of presentation, or the order in which they are ridden.  

Bly notices in President Lincoln's later photographs  "you can see him go into the black."

>  People who are in the black usually give up blame.  A mother once got into the White House and woke Lincoln up at five in the morning, saying that her son had been sent by train to Washington a few days before, had had no sleep, had been assigned guard duty on arriving, had fallen asleep, and now was going to be shot at eight that morning.  if Lincoln had been in the red, he might have shouted for the guards, "Who let this woman in here? Get her out of here!"  If he were in the white he might have said, "Madam, we all have to obey rules.  Your son. didn't obey the rules, and I feel as bad about it as you do, but I can't intervene. H didn't[t say either of those things.  He said, "Well, I guess shooting him wouldn't help him much," and he signed a piece of paper.   We notice that humor comes in with the black.

Bly has pointed out, depending on your myth origin, the horses may be ridden in a different order to represent a different kind of growth.

In the Iron Man myth -- a [[Grimm Brother's fairy tale|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brothers_Grimm]]. a boy becoming a man rides horses given to him by the Wild Man in red, white and black succession.

The Lincoln story is unusual for Bly.  He rarely deals with news, or an event in history, other than to characterize it, leaving our imagination to complete the picture. For example, Ralph Nader is  
said to be riding a White Horse.   






If reading a printed copy, this paper is online at:

* http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/MyIdeaWarehouse.html   OR
* http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/index.html -- my commonplacebook
* http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3 -- my HOME Page






The [[Refresh Application]] makes short HTML files which refresh to another URL,  This gives the user a means of publishing short URL names which refer to a longer winded web address.

The user must have control of the HOME addresses and files (e.g. be able to upload or FTP) on their own server.   And needn't have control over the destination of the [[REFRESH command|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meta_refresh]].

This page is the User Documentation.   

!!! Installation

* download [[commonlib]]
* [[application source|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/bin/refresh_app.txt]] -- "save file"
* $ copy refresh_app.txt  ${SOME_BIN}/refresh_app
* $ chmod +x  ${SOME_BIN}/refresh_app
* $ . refresh_app

A correctly loaded app will return you to this page with this command:

```
$ refresh_doc open

```

Failing that, contact me [[here|MartyMcGowan]].

!!! Usage

Create textfiles, executable shells, with the table of Refresh pages to point to their respective URLs.

There are two commands:

!!!! refresh_url:
* A `writable directory` on the current computer. should be the home of a tree of files on the user's server.
* A `base address` of the remote server, where the refresh re-directs the browser.

!!!! refresh 
*  a local name, appended to the `writable directory`.   It becomes a directory to receive a single file, `index.html` with the refresh URL
* the particular address, again appended to the `base address` of the refreshed URL

!!!! sample script

From the refresh_demo function of the code.


```
    refresh_url $HOME/Dropbox        http://$D_HOME;
    refresh     marty3/LastThings    $D_WARE.html#LastThings;
    refresh     marty3/IdeaWarehouse $D_WARE.html
```

In this example the D_HOME and D_WARE are set outside the existing code to retain some anonymity.

The  `refresh_url` arguments are set as environment variables ''REFRESH_HOME'' and ''REFRESH_URL'', and available to subsequent uses of the `refresh` function.

Having source the //refresh_app// into the current shell, the user may type the commands directly at the command line.

```
$ refresh_url ...
$ refresh ...
```

!!! Scripted

The preferred way is to record the //refresh...// commands in a separate script file, which again be sourced into the current shell.

There are a few lower level functions in the app which are worth explaining here:

* [[bitmeld]], also discussed in [[Local Libraries]], and 
* [[onlyChanged]], almost self-explanatory. in this case used to prevent updating the local file, which anticipates a make-like updating of files to be FTP'ed to the users server.

!!! Caveat

* Have passed ''UNIT'' Test -- that my functions work for me, regardless of origin
* Currently undergoing ''INTEGRATION'' Test -- that installation functions are self-reliant
* Anticipate ''SYSTEM'' test -- await user feedback

[[Early Middle Ages]]

!!! [[Rise of the Carolingians]]

//The Carolingians finally depose the last Merovingian king in 751 A.D., bring all of Francia under their control, and even begin to intervene in Italy, reversing the power balance established during the Roman Empire.//

Battle of Potiers, 732

* C. dominated, rose to prominence
* Clovis, most powerful in the 6th C.
* Flaw was lack of succession.
* Clovis, dies, divides among sons.
* three kingdoms: Neustria, home K, NE of Paris, Austrasia, N of Paris, Burgundy (so, central)
* Last Mv, Dagobert, 635-8
* minority rulers, minimum of 12 yrs
* exploited by other families
* 630s - 60s, "mayor of the palace", controlled access, _and_ appointments: counts, dukes, abbot, bishop
* C's, m.o.p in Austrasia
* battle: C/M, 687 Pepin 2nd, defeated Neustrians
* unity that Romans hadn't achieved,
* 714, P, 2nd died. no legit male sons, successor, illegit grandchild, Theodald,
* Neustrians rebelled, led to

Charles Martel

* Charles Martel, illegitimate son posed as su
* poisoned, escaped 714-19. became m.o.p
* Poitiers, 


on to Byzantium

* secular rulers controlled
* papal election, consecration
* had been controlled by leading families
* election not sufficient, consecration made one the pope
* B. rulers exercised veto over consecration,
* e,g, Martin I, 642, was arrested to Constantinople, guilty, death sentence was commuted by E. Emperor
* Byzantium protected the Popes, Lombards attacked papal property.
* Slavs, Persians, Arabs attacked as well
* 678 - 752, popes were Greek Syrian
* 710, pope visited Byz, last visit until 14thC
* Byz, Leo 3rd, raised taxes to support Const.
* 725 - led to destruction of iconoclasm, 
* Pope refused, churches were confiscated to Byz
* 752, no Greeks as Pope until 15th C, viewed as political (not religious) liberation
* ... why are arabs successful ?   could it be religious images? 
* so who will protect the papacy from the Lombars
* Carolingian, Pepin 3rd, after d. Charles Martel

Pepin, the Short

* consolidated Carolingian dynasty,
* deposed last Merovingian
* 750 to Pope, q. shouldn't C's hold power, papacy exceed to req.
* 751, last Mero, .. 
* P, anointed by the Pope, north of the Alps, first ever crossing.
* C's have to assume protection of papacy from the L's
* no tradition of F's south of the Alps,
* P3, 755,56 succeeded 
* similar turning point as P no/Alps
* = large steps out of Early towards middle

Conclusion

* 751 last M deposed
* C arrangement w/ papacy
* C intervened in Italian matters
* cooperation continued 
* future: Charlemagne

!!! Rosemary

Watching the preparations for public distribution of the Eucharist at St Benedict's mass [[today,|18th November 2018]] I'm readily reminded of Rosemary Reilly's taking charge while we were on the ministry team at St Michael's of Cranford.    She's gone, the better part of 20 years now, but she would have none of the fumbling start we had been used to.   The first pair of ministers receiving the host would immediately receive their ciboria to distribute the host to the remainder of the special ministers; the next pair would receive the cups, now the "chalice" according to the vatican-mandated GRIC.   By the time the first four special ministers had received, and in the time it took the priest to reach his central position at the rail, the second pair of ministers of the host would be close behind, followed by ministers of the cup.   The last pairs to their positions were those who first received their form.  The whole process took less than two minutes.   This was in the halcyon days  of the late '80s, early '90s, when lay initiative was encouraged and accepted.  Rosemary was among the un-bashful.






The [[runfrom]] function solves the problem of unnecessary cd and pushd, popd commands in our functions,   In these sources, the demo_runfrom functions shows a proper use.   It executes the ls -l command in the home directory, regardless of where it was exectued.

[[runfrom]] itself

# //return//s if in the first-argument directory [FAD], OR continues:
# goes to the FAD by a //pushd//
# retrieves the calling command by //myname 2//
# executes the calling command with the remaining arguments,
# //pops// the directory stack, returning from the called directory, and finally
# //return//s an error (which is actually success) since the calling function relies on

Here is the code, with supplementary functions:

!!! [[runfrom_code]]: 
{{runfrom_code}}






```
app_pause () 
{ 
    : date: 2019-07-13;
    : pause execution, displaying the arguments;
    read -p "$@. RETURN? " < /dev/tty
}
demo_runfrom () 
{ 
    : date: 2019-09-10;
    app_pause ENTRY;
    runfrom $HOME $* || {    return;  };
    ls -l $*;
}
indir () 
{ 
    : date: 2017-05-29;
    : date: 2018-10-09;
    report_notdirectory $1 && return 1;
    pushd $1 > /dev/null;
    eval ${@:2};
    popd 1>&2 > /dev/null
}
myname () 
{ 
    : ~ [n];
    : returns name of caller OR callers caller ...;
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    echo ${FUNCNAME[${1:-1}]}
}
runfrom () 
{ 
    : usage: ~ DIRECTORY function args OR return;
    : date: 2019-09-10;
    : date: 2020-02-04 simplify, test using indir;
    [[ $PWD = $(indir $1 pwd) ]] && return;
    pushd $1 1>&2;
    shift;
    local cmd=$(myname 2);
    $cmd $@;
    popd 1>&2;
    return 1
}
```

! Stonebridge Mens Club

This is the user's guide to the [[SBMC Master spreadsheet|https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1neC5TfM5-YWgt7H-4Gy4wSY34KVwZFDXVp0Xzx5fN2o/edit#gid=774312681]]

The sheet's objective is to produce an instant update of the Men's Club active roster from a list of the men the community.  As necessary by-products, list of men whose membership is expiring, since the time time their dues come due, a list of former members and a list of those whom never been members, at least since 2016.

!! Users Guide

Enter the personnel data on ~MensClub worksheet, columns A thru G

When updating dues payment, copy the year from'' latest'' to ''prior'' fields and enter the new dues year in ''latest.''

No need to update the ''changed'' field unless it's a:

* new entry, or
* the address, email, or cell phone changed,

If this was done manually, enter your initials in the ''edited'' field

Columns to the right, N thru S, are updated when a dues-payer is entered on the ''latest'' column for the new dues year.

This is set to a default option, explained below.

!! The Worksheets

!!! ~MensClub2018 -- in two parts:

* data entry, includes //latest// and //prior// year fields. when the record was //changed //and who //edited.//
* fields N thru S, where the list of paid members is returned

!!! filter -- with fields:

* key, usually an email, if not last,first
* years, sums these, explained below
* latest, and, 
* prior, then the 
* data fields from the ~MensClub2018 sheet
* a filler,
* key, where it's generated
* countif, looking for 
* duplicates, repeated to collapse unique

!!! collecting;

*key, -- from the filter
*status -- based on the years, see the table, below
*years, -- from the filter
*Renewed/Active, select one of two options which determine the membership status, explained below. Important is the pair of columns, H and I where the four possible status are listed: ''never, lapsed, expire'' or ''member'' are tabulated, again more later
*a selector, default to ``member`` may use any of the labels in column H, as above.
*first -- discussed below, how the selector group is retrieived from the entire database.  this first "first" while be loaded with #NA's as a key to which records need display in columns N thru S
*T thru W -- used to compare, hopefully for the last time. with the existing member list from the treasurer.

!!! on [[20th September 2018]]

Honorable [[Senator Booker]]

When we Democrats control the Senate, this proposal should guarantee bi-partisan support from the Republicans:

Committee Chairs and party seats on a committee should be apportioned  relative  to the number of senators of the various parties.  For example, with 100 committees in the senate, and a 55 - 43 - 2 split among the parities,   55 committees would be chaired by the majority party, 43 by the second party, and 2 by the third (independent) party.

The majority party in this case, with 12 more committees to chair than the second party would choose the first 12 committees, the parties would then alternate, as in the sports drafts, where a minority party would get the last choice in the first thru Nth rounds until their choices were satisfied.

If there are but say 60 committees, with the same (55,43,2) proportions,  then it's 33, 26, and 1.   The majority party would choose the first 7 chairs. etc...

This would establish the Democrats as the party who doesn't extract retribution and treats their opponents as fellow legislators, if not humans.

Respectfully,

   ~ Martin J McGowan III

!!! timely

Start with this reading of [[New Rules]]

!!! opinion

Let's lay the opinions out first:  the [[shell sh-bang|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shebang_(Unix)]] is the most over-used and needless feature of shell programming. I disagree with an overwhelming consensus of shell instructional sequence.  It should be the penultimate lesson, rather than the first or second.   

What I'm presenting here is one of two approaches to minimizing sh-bang's in shell programming.  The shell should be a programming language, not a "scripting" language.  I believe the [[shell function |https://leanpub.com/shellfunctions]] is the most useful and underutilized feature of the the various shell  implementations.  Since the '90s and certainly the '00s, the bash shell is the preeminent choice of shell practitioners. The sh-bang has been around since version 7 Unix, when one of its two developers added the the feature. (see the above reference)  The sh-bang is properly used for scripts in non-shell languages, for example Perl, Python, PHP, Tcl, Scheme, etc.  The practice laid out here asks and answers the question: of what use is the sh-bang to a shell programmer?  I'm trying to understand the need, since the shell is the default command language of the user's terminal window.

!!! shell libraries

For quite a few years, I've avoided the sh-bang initiated shell script, since I run commands from my terminal window, running a shell.   Any shell function I choose to run from that window has access to all the functions I've ever written and still find useful.   The terminal is already a suitable shell environment, so the last thing a function needs is a sh-bang declaration, since it's already running a shell.   All my applications are composed entirely of shell functions, sourced from shell libraries.   

The problem, if there is one, is to produce an application without regard to a collection of libraries.  I've placed [[collections on GitHub to standardize|https://github.com/applemcg/shelf/blob/master/shelf.org]] the features of an extended library practice. Here, I take up the work to produce a stand-alone application from functions in a single library, where those functions may have scattered dependencies.

!!! the application

The discussion at [[App from Lib]] begins the work to collect all the functions into a single file.  This is now my preferred [[approach to take, and  presented here|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/software/onlyOneShBang.html]].  The second code sample is the ''sh-bang script.''   Through the magic of the [[Unix Link (ln) command|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ln_(Unix)]], any number of command names may use this identical script, no not by copying, but by linking.   What that means is any command (file) is linked to the identical copy of the executable.  The only difference is the name of the command.   Each command exists as a separate name in a directory, but different from incomplete operating systems the text of that command file is the single instance of the file, in this case, sh-bang.

To manage that usage, a very [[small function library, the banglib|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/software/onlyOneShBang.html#sec-2-2]] manages the individual connections.

If you have just created a //bangableApp// application, this command

> $ bang_iam  bangableApp
links the //bangableApp// to the sh-bang code.  As a side-effect, the names of the using applications are saved in a local file.    Since this is in the early stages of development, testing, expanding the use cases, the command `bang_saved` restores the formerly banged files to the new version of `sh-bang`







In a discussion[[ comparing shell arrays|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/software/arraysProCon.html]] to more function approaches, I offered a few functions to simplify lists in the shell.

!!! skills acquired:

* functions to define functions
* "smart" functions -- those with default commands
* deferred positional parameter
* bash repeated name convention

The ''list_of'' function, defined in this section: [[Functional|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/software/arraysProCon.html#sec-4-2]] is the centerpiece.   It can be entered on the command line:

```
$ list_of () { eval "$1 () { \${1:-echo} ${*:-2}; }"; }
```
see the reference above to unpack the description and use.

!! Functions to write [[SmartFunctions]]

These few functions expand on the idea of [[Shell Lists]].  The heart of both these ideas is the ''eval'' builtin is used to create functions

!!! skills acquired:

* refresh prior exercise: functions writing functions
* introduce assertion checking
* using a template string in function definition
* show default use, and purpose of general use

!!! the functions

The `smart_def` function is similar to the ''list_of'' function, just more formal.  In this little exercise, the name, ''def_functions'' is defined to hold the list of defined functions.
In addition to smart_def, it relies on ''report_notargcount'' and ''report_usage'' functions.

```
$ smart_def def_functions smart_def report_notargcount report_usage
$
$ def_functions
smart_def report_notargcount report_usage
$
$ def_functions declare -f
smart_def () 
{ 
    : date: 2017-06-10;
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    report_notargcount 2 $# listName member ... && return 1;
    local boiler=": mfg: $(myname 2);: date: $(date +%Y-%m-%d)";
    eval "$1 () { $boiler; \${@:-echo} $(args_uniq ${*:2}); }"
}
report_notargcount () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    [[ $2 -ge $1 ]] && return 1;
    report_usage need at least $1 arg/s: ${*:3}
}
report_usage () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    : date: 2018-03-30;
    echo USAGE $(myname 3): $* 1>&2
}
$
$ declare -f def_functions
def_functions () 
{ 
    : mfg: pick;
    : date: 2018-06-22;
    ${@:-echo} smart_def report_notargcount report_usage
}
```

The opening command uses `smart_def`  to define a //smart function//, named ''def_functions''.  It will contain the name of the defined functions used to display the needed code of this exercise: ''smart_def, report_notargcount,'' and ''report_usage''.   Nothing is output at this point; the function has been defined.

The next command, ''def_functions'' itself, by default, lists its member names.

Executed with arguments, in this case:

```
$ def_functions declare -f 
```
displays the contents of the functions.  The //builtin//  `declare -f` displays it's function arguments.  To make the point more explicit, and not shown above, this command is equivalent:

```
$ declare -f $(def_functions)
```
The last example shows the behavior of displaying the body of ''def_functions''

Notice the difference of the behavior, with and without the `$( ... )` idiom

The code of ''def_functions''  explains the behavior with and without arguments.   The default command is the builtin ''echo'' command.  If the function has any arguments, they are executed instead.  For example, down the road, you might see:


```
$ def_functions extract_shdocs
```
!!! future functions

In an IOU moment, a future exercise will  show the ''args_uniq'' and ''myname'' functions. 

Also, you might expect the the ''report_usage'' is a common feature of the family of //report_// functions.

The boiler plate includes '': mfg:'' and '': date:'' tags.  These anticipate a future where we employ //shdocs//,  thinking //javadocs, pydocs//, ...

Also, the ''args_uniq'' function has a role to play in the ''smart_add'' and ''smart_del'' functions which maintain the list.









Smart Functions are characterized by this bit of syntax


```
fun_name () { ${*:-command} ...; }  # for example
home     () { ${*:-echo} $HOME/Dropbox; }
```
a smart function which has a directory or file arguments may be called a "smart file".

an alternate, and quite common usage is to create a list:


```
fun_list () { ${*:-echo} fun_{this,that,other,list}; }
```
which takes advantage of the Bash Shell's Name expansion.







See my software diary for [[today|13th April 2019]], where I developed collections.   Here's the collection_names function:


```
collect_names () 
{ 
    : MFG a SMART _COLLECTION;
    : rather than assume they are FUNCTIONS, just return NAMES;
    : date: 2019-04-12;
    local mfg="    : mfg: $(myname)";
    eval "${1}_collection () { $mfg; \${*:-echo}  ${*:2} \$(myname); }"
}

```

And an example of its use:


```
collect_namesEG () 
{ 
    : demonstarate collect_functions;
    : date: 2019-04-12;
    collect_names graf "fun_{words,callgraf,alltype} app_fun{uses,call}"
}


```

St Mary's Librarian through '02






At one time, Katie and I were the "donate" button on the[[ StoryCorps web site.|https://storycorps.org/]]

The nostalgic moment we had was the [[NYC Steam Pipe Explosion|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_New_York_City_steam_explosion]].   We had just finished our photo shoot, (note to self, find the video where the photo appears), and stepped out of the booth in Grand Central.   Within a minute, an NYC (transit?) cop is ushering, as in "shooing" a few dozen commuters around the kiosk in the center of the side lobby. "What's going on?" we wonder.   Within not much more than another minute, she's shooing them around the other way, and directing them up the stairs to an exit.   We dutifully follow.

No fright, but plenty of caution:   Katie had a floral on black dress, easily recalled from the ash fallout from the explosion.   We had no idea what had happened.  Recall the date is within a few years of the  Nine Eleven Disaster.  The news came in with a cell-phone call to Pat at home with the TV coverage.   We walked west, finding cover from store awnings, until about 8th street, and headed south to the corner (32nd st?) below Penn Station where we adjourned at the 'Pork Pit', or some such better establishment.

Stroll and Roam (https://roamresearch.com/) are not competitors. I use both, and recommend Roam highly. 

Each app has its strengths and drawbacks. Here is a general comparison:

''Advantages of Roam''

*Block level transclusion
*Outliner features (zoom in and out, expand and collapse points, etc)
*Graph overview (though you can add the [[TiddlyMap plugin to Stroll|http://tiddlymap.org/]]
*Fast code blocks like /time, /date picker, etc
*Numerous hotkeys

''Advantages of Stroll''

*Free
*Local file, your data is yours, no privacy concerns or fear of losing your data if they get hacked or close their doors
*Text formatting, CSS options for tables, etc are superior
*Infinitely customizable UI
*Widgets, macros and other goodies built in
*An extensive list of plugins (see the [[TiddlyWiki toolmap|https://dynalist.io/d/zUP-nIWu2FFoXH-oM7L7d9DM]])
*Multiple options for viewing references

Here's an effort, let's call it research into  [[tagging files|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/software/tagging.html#tagging]].   
 
This page serves as both a [[manual page|manpp]] and user documentation, Here is [[the code|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/software/tagging.html#tag_code]].

!!! NAME

taglib -- tag files

!!! SYNOPSIS

```
$ source taglib     # loads the app
$ tag_code          # the code listing
$ tag               # lists current tags
$ tag tagname       # lists files with tagname
$ tag Name file ... # tags files with Name as tag
```

!!! DESCRIPTION

The taglib contains functions to:

* tag files 
* list tagnames
* list files with a tagname
* list all tags on a file
* list all tagged files locations

!!! FILES

relative to the user's HOME

* `.tag`-- tagnames are directories
* `.tag/name` --  directory of linked files tagged with "name"
* `.tag/.lib/inode.txt` -- lists inode fullpath for every tagged file

!!! EXAMPLE

```
$ tag html *.html
$ tag html               # shows file names
$ tags example.html      # shows all tags for the file
$ tag_files example.html # shows file path to tagged file

```
!!! WARNING

Files should be tagged from their local directory.

Tag namespace ( directories ) is global, therefore, for example index.html files, likely frequent names, will collide.

Tagging is best accomplished on time-stamped media files.

In [[The Case of the Missing iPhone]], which unfolded and was completely solved yesterday -- until my newly acquired good habit lapses -- is a lesson in prudent care of one's most sacred possessions.

In the middle, Pat offered the notion that "you can do without it for a few days".  With which I gladly agreed.

But to the Case.

It was a normal shopping trip, with my pen-recorded shopping list tucked into the money-clip side of my credit-card wallet.   The money clip side being reserved for paper cash and things like cash: Mets tickets, future track parlays, un-expired raffle tickets, restaurant receipts waiting for scanning, ...  I added the shopping list to the collection only recently  since "tucked under the band of the baseball cap" wasn't a guaranteed clothing item.  This is the first debit item in the fold, since all others are in the credit column.

In the course of unfurling the STWW items on entering the local Stop and Shop:  iPhone, shopping list, exchange two pairs of glasses, for the first time, I set the iPhone in the kid-seat side of the cart, making sure the leg gates were closed, lest the phone should slide out on a tight turn or quick start/stop.  Since my list is now in a fixed place, unbundling my pockets is the annoying part of the procedure, and no doubt is why the iPhone found the kid-seat.

The trip was otherwise uneventful.  The list had fewer than a dozen items, a typical number leading me to prefer the DIY line, with eight stalls for personal check-out.   This reflection leads me to recall, as I stood there, now fast friend BernieSchutzberg, passing took a moment to notice me, thus reminding me of the need to recall his name.   We shared the trouble using the scanner, but happy to have such a feature which encourages more frequent, less abundant trips.  I'm personally reminded my calling such a  BobbyRalicki memorial shopping trip, after our times with him and Toni in Pittsburgh when he can't go two days without a call to the grocery store.  

In any case, I'm paying close attention to the phone in the basket but am thinking "this is time to remember Bernie's name now and forever".   And as I walk out, "Bernie" is my mantra.   One thing always in the back of my mind is the tendency of the iPhone is it's apparent preference to produce a "pocket dial".   Which may be my excuse for not putting it back in my jeans pocket, the other alternative may be the bernie mantra.   I"ll have to share an edited version of this story when we next meet.  

I parked the cart in the shade of a tree at the corner of the S & S driveway, which saves me the trouble of pushing it thru the street and over a curb.   I'll do this when I've but four or fewer plastic -- save this story for later -- bags.   I pick the bags from the cart, but must have overlooked the iPhone still laying there. This is the last moment I could have closed this saga without it's becoming noteworthy.   I cross the street, and into the second row of the lot, where I notice a young girl on her cell phone in the row behind my car and one slot to the left, right as she's facing.  The bags are loaded into the back seat.   I hop in the front and proceed.   I'm out on Perrineville Road, heading south, adjusting to the right lane, as faster traffic will want the left.   I'm settled in the first quarter mile, not yet to the back gate of Concordia, and note the absence of music.  My default setting is Bluetooth, and I'd been using it on the way to the store.  "Where's the music? Oops, Where's the iPhone?" it's not in the console where it might be, but more important, it's not in my pocket, either.   From the right lane, it's a simple matter to slow down and let three cars past, make the U-turn in the three lane road, and hasten back to the S&S parking lot.

My thought towards my usual parking area was "see if you can spot the cart where you left it".   A good, but evaporated plan.   Park the car and see if you can find it in the just-returned carts in the cart-bay, it wasn't three minutes since you left.   Good fortune would have the young cart-pusher come by, which gave me the opportunity to offer my dilemma.  We searched the dozen or so best choices to no avail.   "Let's see if it was turned in at the service counter".   More "no such luck".    At which point i left the description: iPhone 8, black case,  it's number, and "call this number: Pat's phone", she has it at home.   And I returned home with the groceries and a few ideas.

One, a vague understanding of a "find your phone" feature Apple offers, the other involved patiently waiting for a call from the S&S service desk.  On arriving, Pat was my first stop, explaining what I thought I'd done, forgetting the Bernie moment.  After sitting down at this iMac, it quickly became apparent the better "app" was the one an iPhone.  I thought now how fortunate we were to both be using the iPhone, having already apologized to more tech-savy McGowan brothers about having been on the Android phone, one of which was the dreaded Huawei.  So, using Pat's phone, I first logged into here Apple account and quickly realized the Find iPhone app defaults to her phone, or more accurately, the Apple account one is logged into.  Bless that internet.   So, back to my iMac, where i share data in the Notes app.  From this I was able to log into my Apple account, and sure enough, there were my devices. Poking on Marty's iPhone, and in a few seconds, there was an icon sitting in the parking lot in front of the Concordia Stop & Shop.

At this point a digression into the features of the GPS facilities of the modern smart phone is in order.  You see, I'm one of four holders of the seminal patent: [[#5559520, Wireless Information System for Acquiring Location Related Information|https://patents.google.com/patent/US5559520A/en]].   Not to belabor its development, suffice it to say, it is the basis of most (all?) mobile apps requiring remote location.   We called it [["Public Lojack"|https://www.lojack.com/]].  With the icon on the map, no decision, I'm heading back to the Stop & Shop.

As i hop in the car and head out, I see the phone icon move away from the store, and apparently out into the parking lot.  After I'm about half way to the store, the icon isn't moving any more; the shopper has left the cart where they unloaded it.  Let's see if the icon starts to move.  Was it scooped into the shoppers car?   Apparently not.   My memory is a bit fuzzy at this point.  When I'm within a half-mile of the store (it's about a 3.5 mile trip) two things happen:  i see the icon jump to a point directly in front of the store and the gal at the service desk dials Pat's phone, the one i'm using.  Oh yes, One of the great, necessary features of the Find iPhone app is you can store a phone number to call associated with the missing phone. It further suggests it leaves that number on the main screen of the lost phone.   That experiment is yet to be verified.   I didn't have a chance to inquire about what she saw, as she was inquiring about what she would see to identify the phone.   I was so flummoxed, it took more than a few seconds to identify my relationship to the figures there: Maura, a young Teddy, and Chip.   That done I was within a few hundred yards of the store.

I parked, entered, and joined a 3-person line at the busy service desk, chatting with the next fellow, who was without knowing it, doing a good job of settling me down.     We were still chatting when the lady service manager remembered me from having left the report, and while she was still on another conversation slid the iPhone onto the counter where I collected it kissing it to Pat's iPhone.

And Pat takes full credit for this insight:

> If you want to avoid losing one thing, only set it down with at least one other.














[[Michelle|https://thecollegespy.com/meet-michelle]],

  i caught your appearance on this evening's The News Hour.  good work.
 
  I was the beneficiary of an unwritten quota system to the class of '66 at MIT.   The [[Bakke decision|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regents_of_the_Univ._of_Cal._v._Bakke]]  followed within a decade.  At  which point I thought of this solution, taking the college/university off the hook for college admissions policy.   

Your appearance helped clarify my thinking.   The issue of the moment is "to test or not to test".  Imagine that a school offered, "we're going to offer two admission queues, the tested and the untested; you can choose either queue".   to be fair, the number of people admitted would be proportional to the number of people in either queue.   

And here's where Bakke comes into play.  Who says there are only two queues.  You are allowed to enter your application in any number of queues.  And, the institution isn't bound to specific queues:   any queues the applicants self-nominate is an allowable queue to be served.  The only requirement the institution is obliged to serve is a threshold of a single student's criteria.  i.e. a school which admits 1000 students would be required to serve a queue with more than 0.1% of the applicants. e.g.  I don't think a queue labeled "west central minnesotan's" would have met the threshold.  but i'll bet "upper midwest" might have, or maybe not.  i had two frat bro who'd graduated from Boston Latin,  who had a high school chum who had gotten in to Hahvahd.   They could name 8 Latin friends with "double 8s" who made neither.  However my rural MN, math = 740 qualified on some queue.

Thank you for your advocacy.  Anything I can do to help?  I'll be with you and yours.

Respectfully,

 ~ Martin (Marty) J McGowan III

  http://applemcg.github.io/ -=-  a McGowan from APPLEton, seriously.







[[Early Middle Ages]];

!! The House of Islam

!!! introduction
* Justinian conquest attempt over-taxed Byzantine Empire
* 620s Heraclitus attacked Persia, was successful by 630
* Persians would be destroyed by Arabs 
* Islam from 632
!!! Arabia
* Bedouins, razia -- cattle rading
* South A. relatively well watered
* Mecca was a trading town, coastal
* pagan polytheists
* Allah was one of many gods

!!! Muhamad

* b. 670s
* major religions founded by men in their 30s
* M. married well
* M received revalations, left Mecca for Medina
* invited by Med leaders, 622, the hajira, Islam yr 1
* M united Arabian tribes behind revalations
* M captured Mec in 630

!!! Beliefs
* Islam ~ submission
* monotheism
* Allah is the one God
* M had personal J'sh Chr 
* Resurrection of the body
* More Jewish no pork, circumcision
* No priests
* Commentators on the religious law
* M presented as fulfillment of J & C traditions
* this is the final 
* Abraham was first Muslim
* Distinction:  M is not devine, nor is Jesus

!!! Spread

* captured Damascus, Jerusalem in 630
* Egypt by 640
* n. Africa by 690s
* did not capture Constantinople ( 674, 717 )
* Persians and eastern empire were taxed
* surprise on Arab side
* opponents expected divided Arabs
* A's operated in favorable (desert) environment
* A's withdrew into desserts, but not in
* N. France, where camels didn't work well,
* Religious zeal have A's cohesion, energy
> Once, the Arabs were a wretched race, whom you could tread underfoot with impunity.  We were reduced to eating dogs and lizards.  But, for our glory, God has raised up a prophet among us.

* Pacification explains spread. dissipated the A vs A typical tribalism
* religious scholars justified conquests, became jihad.  original "striving", effort vs temptation.
* Jihad is in Koran ~ 4 times
* jihad idea is worked out over time. 7th & 8th C's
* world should mirror perfect unity of one God: Allah
* House of Islam is where Allah holds sway,
* Other part is "House of War"
* Jihad then was to accomplish rid the world with conqest of the House of War.
* goal: political unity of world.  did not mean religious unity.
* pagans may be members of HoI
* J's and C's may continue to practice their own religion as "Peoples of the Book"
* Jizya (tax) allows Js, Cs, to remain so.  Tax was counter productive
* Early 8th c, regular diplomatic contacts replaced absorbing HoW in HoI
* Jihad rose again in the Crusades

!!! Questions
* Religion Important to Early Islam; why not in similar Christian history
* Turn other cheek vs I's jihad
* Why the difference.  Not explained by "bad" Mohammad vs "good" Jesus.  Historians prefer historical thoujght, not good/bad values
* Ch had now territory for 3 Cs
* Spiritual warfare was part of early HoI

!!! Europe
* A's and Berbers from N.Afr, conquered Spain. vm 711.   first was a raid, not to be a battle. Tariq, slave, iklled VG king
* By 716, most of Iberian  to Duero and Ebro Rivers, not hte mountainous
* By  720s into sw france, Tolouse, 
* Charles Martel 732, slowed expansion at Poitiers.

!! Conclusion

* from Arabia, frontiers fo Persia and Byzantum
* 716 into spain
* 720s 30s into spain
* europe revlieved by Charles Martel.
* sowed seeds 0f next change

A letter to BobSimcoe, encouraging him to read [[Simon Winchester's The Perfectionists.|http://www.librarything.com/work/20935820/edit/159373944]]

>   I've set your dad's book, Metals in America, next to me here at the computer, and have just read your collective introduction.   i was moved to pick up the book after having just finished Simon Winchester's "The Perfectionists".   My thoughts as I went thru Winchester's book was to address a letter to you, Rob and Tim.   You will find there is something here for all of you.   I deferred leaping on that idea, realizing there's likely a point of intersection with your dad's work, and saved this letter until I finished.  I'll take up Metals in America next.

>   Trying to restrain from making this a book review, Winchester orders his chapters in the order of magnitude precision has reached.   He dates  precision's origin to an event in the early 19th c,  giving historical references to classic times.   His fascination dates from his just pre-teen years when his father (metal worker in the UK) came home with a set of guide blocks.    The story wraps up with the state of measurement, how the six physical units of measure are now all defined with time.  

 > I thought of Rob's and Tim's interests as he gives fair play to our penetration of the Universe, and how devices have fostered intellectual property rights.    He gives forensic analysis of the Hubble mistake and correction, the Challenger disaster, ... Among others, I forgot which, but his analysis is almost too precise for all but the expert.  In a few areas, you'd find yourself among.  

 > So, time for the Preface and chapter of "[[The History of Metals in America.|http://www.librarything.com/work/22745178/book/165523819]]"

In response to Vince's question:  I'm watching Thunderball; didn't you see some of that being filmed?

* When?   thinking spring '64, sophomore year,
* Where?  Paradise Island, Bahama's

Mom & Dad's reaction was to the $155 off-budget expenses: gas (1/6) for Ed Sullivan's ~DeSoto, round trip Boston-Ft Lauderdale. Round-Trip flight to Nassau.   Five nights at a dive in the eastern end of town discovered the year before (so maybe it was '65 when we went).   Our two hosts were, no kidding, Benson ~McDonald and William ~McKinney, literally defining blackness.  Entertainment was King Eric and his Knights, who I believe were also shown in the movie. 

Paradise Island is/was swimmable as some of our party were ambitious and did (swim). I did not.   With our snorkels, masks and fins, the people running the boat thought we were swimmers/extras in the film = free 5 min ride.  In those days, Paradise Island was "undeveloped", now there is a monster hotel on it.

The filming we saw is when Bond and his contact (woman) were in a boat and rescuing Domino, another one of the Bond Girls, from the water.  It was in a cove on the North side of the island.   They came ashore right in front of our group.   I've a memory of a photo I got with one of the girls just out of the boat, in a fish-net swim suit.   Its remarkable feature is the guy with the Mich St football jersey whose jaw is so agape, he should be swallowing sand.  Where is that photo now.

Thanks for the opportunity to exercise the memory.

n this period of [[Time On Your Hands]] TOYH, i had a mental
phenomenon we all must often encounter: that of a random thought or
memory triggered by a seemingly disconnected stream of thought
itself.

In my case, at the moment, 6:20 am on Friday, march 27, in Monroe
township NJ, while putting together the acronym of this note, TOYH,
the random thought was parking a rental car at my brother Kevin's
apartment complex in Tucson AZ.  Just pulling into a covered spot, Pat
with me. In the passenger seat.  And sort of a removed-from-body
view : looking at the car from behind on and  the
passenger side, maybe a foot or two from coming to a stop as I was
driving.

I was assembling the acronym in my head T O Y H. In my head, thinking
of how to present it for a readership.

And the image of parking the car appeared.  I think it was dark —
black maybe.  Pat didn’t get out of the car, the scene was more
like a GIF image: two seconds of slight motion.

Meanwhile, what was it that required an acronym.  T O Y H.  Time On
Your Hands in this time of self-quarantine and social-distancing.

The time on my hands came after viewing an NYC-Arts production with
Paula Zahn showcasing the the Jewish Holocaust Museum on PBS 13 .
The special centered on an exhibit: too ... Not  long Ago, Not
 Far Away, about the horrors of the Auschwitz-Birkenau
extermination camps of the Nazis in WWII.

She featured a handful of survivors of the camps, book-ended by two
principal figures of the museum: Bruce Ratner and Ron Lauder.  They
are both contemporaries of min , plus or minus a year.  Metro NYC,
money, and dedicated to the preservation of memories wrapped in the
clothing of the Holocaust.

On to the thought: after the show concluded, credits rolled, I thought
about my time in the area —- battery Park, six years on state street
and my time in “the City:, what better way to refresh those moments
than with a t.  peek into the New Yorker Today app on this iPad.  An
article “The Trump o-clock follies” by. Susan B Glasser gave added
currency to the word “mendacious”

I think in know what that means, but lets check..  So a browse”
dictionary:mendacious” produced a list lead by dictionary dot com and
Merrimack Webster.  My age prejudices led my to the second on the
list: Merrimack-Webster; definition #2: telling a lie.  that’s easy
enough.  “He’s lying”.  So too said dictionary.co.  Posing the
question, which of those prominent authorities should I prefer?  what
else are they offering to keep me attracted.  Plot spoiler: Merrimack
Webster.  Why?

It was in the added attractions where they shined in my eyes.  They
offered a history of the word, in this case mendacious.  It first
appeared in print in the 16th century.  offering ... ( They both
... In addition th the historical reference, m/w offered scans of
recent news articles with with the word in context.

Bias in the “added attractions” where m/w showed its commitment to the
language. Other words appearing in 1646 were (~ some ..) additionally,
jejune non-existent, testosterone, ...

Dictionary.com’s bait was aquifer quiz on slang: an 11 question multiple choice
quiz where it took me to the fifth question to realize the correct
response was always their first choice.  The best I can offer them is
that their randomizes code wasn’t working in either the browser or on
their server.

Also, their contemporary quotes where from the “”daily Beast”, where
the M/W were from The NY Times.  .

Dictionary.com has a different audience, no doubt.  Lets give them credit for
encouraging the early learners an opportunity to explore this language
we live in.

The [[token function]] is a function returning a key-board entered token. 

Here it is:

```
token () 
{ 
    : lesson: how do i turn off echo in a terminal?;
    : https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5633472/how-do-i-turn-off-echo-in-a-terminal;
    while true; do
        printf "token: " > /dev/tty;
        read -s token < /dev/tty;
        [[ ${#token} -gt 5 ]] && { 
            echo $token;
            return
        };
        echo token is NOT gt 5 > /dev/tty;
    done
}
```

The purpose of course, is to collect a "token", e.g. password, to supply to a crypt program reading an encrypted password file, whose name is undisclosed and on a private un-networked file.

The last lesson was solved at stack-overflow.  I'd been reading in shell scripts for a while, mostly as a pause in a shell function  to display traces, values etc.

I thought it useful to require the token to be six or more characters, in this age of snooping.   It's working fine.   I'll document the library when I can change passwords on the fly and save the encrypted file safely.

While composing in TW on my computer, a file may be linked using the `file://` protocol favorably using the relative path.  When copied (via ftp) to the server, these links don't work.   This tends to discourage using TW to link to other pages, not in the same Wiki.

Sometimes you want to see notes side by side:

*To review one and write in another
*To compare and contrast two ideas
*To have a reference sheet or list of snippets open while you are writing

In Roam you would do this by adding a page to the sidebar. In Scroll you do it by opening two columns of tiddlers.

<span class="bluebox">

''Activities:''

#Hide the sidebar using the <<icon {{$:/core/images/chevron-right}} "">> icon at the top of the sidebar.

#Hold down the Shift button and click on these two links, [[Marty McGowan]]. It should appear in a separate column to the right.
#Do the same (shift-click) for the tiddler [[Muffin 1]].

</span>

Now you can view or edit tiddlers in either column, side-by-side!

Note: If you close tidders and only one tiddler is left, Stroll will revert back to one column.

!Diverting tiddlers between columns

<span class="bluebox">

''Activity:''

#Now click the <<icon {{$:/_sq/Stories/icons/divert-left.svg}} "">> and <<icon {{$:/_sq/Stories/icons/divert-right.svg}} "">> icons at the top of the tiddler to 'divert' the [[Muffin 1]] tiddler back and forth between the two columns.

</span>

!'Folding' (compressing) tiddlers

<span class="bluebox">

#Click the <<icon {{$:/core/images/fold-button}} "">> in any tiddler multiple times to compress or 'fold' the contents of the tiddler. Folding tiddlers makes it faster to scroll up and down the columns. Click the button again to 'unfold' the tiddler.

</span>

!Switching between one- and two-column mode

<span class="bluebox">

''Activity:''

#Open the sidebar back up. You will see a <<icon {{$:/_sq/Stories/icons/bars.svg}} "">> button in the sidebar. It is only visible when both columns are open. Click the button to return to one column mode. Click it again to open the two column mode again.

</span>

now before I trade on any stock, i  update the [[Recommendation]],   stocks with an //act on// field are updated on the day I set that field.

!! The [[Update Interval]]

Key to managing the job is scheduling data collection for individual stocks.   The //analyst// rating is the key to the process and the most valuable parameter in buy-sell decisions.    Here's a chart of //analyst// rating vs months to next evaluation:
[img alt="Rating vs Next Eval" width="256
"[RatingVsNext.png]]
So, the lower the //analyst// rating the greater the update interval.  For example, an analyst rating of 4.5, is about a 1 year interval to the next evaluation.  A rating of 8 or better is within the next six months.

Which is why the sheet is sorted on //16//.   On the evaluation sheet, I've a column to produce that field.  This sheet hides most of the work.  Every so often, those dates which are in the past produce an entry in the empty column, and when the sheet is sorted, yet another sheet is set up to take values from a manual inspection of the Fidelity pages where the reports are collected.

Tiddlers have two sides to them: a viewing mode and an editing mode.

!Viewing mode

*The buttons at the top right of the tiddler are called the 'viewtoolbar'.
**<<icon {{$:/core/images/edit-button}} "">> takes you to editing mode
**<<icon {{$:/core/images/close-button}} "">> closes the tiddler. It is now hidden but you can search for it in the searchbar or the tabs.
**<<icon {{$:/core/images/down-arrow}} "">> opens a menu of other buttons.
**You will find out about the other buttons in another step.

!Editing mode

*In editing mode you can change the tiddler title, add tags, add text, and make other advanced changes.
*<<icon {{$:/core/images/delete-button}} "">> deletes the tiddler
*<<icon {{$:/core/images/cancel-button}} "">> cancels changes made to the tiddler and returns to viewing mode
*<<icon {{$:/core/images/done-button}} "">> saves changes and returns to viewing mode

<span class="bluebox">

''Activity:''

Click the <<icon {{$:/core/images/edit-button}} "">> icon in the top right corner of the Welcome to Stroll tiddler to go into editing mode and see what it looks like. Then click either the <<icon {{$:/core/images/cancel-button}} "">> button or the <<icon {{$:/core/images/done-button}} "">> button and return to viewing mode.

</span>






```
value_lock ()
{
    set $(myname 2) $*
    report_notfunction $1 && return 1;
    [[ -f .$1 ]] || {
        : default value is empty
        echo > .$1;
        touch .value_lock;
        ( cat .value_lock;
        echo $1 ) | sort -u > .value_tmp && mv .value_{tmp,lock}
    };
    [[ $# -gt 1 ]] && {
        : remaining arguments are stored, allowing phrase
        echo ${*:2} > .$1
    };
    cat .$1
}
```
As a trade-off, to eliminate local variables, set the name of the calling function: `myname 2` as the first argument, followed by any others.  Any arguments, possibly a phrase is stored in the .{name} file.

usage looks like:

```
$ aa () { value_lock $*; }
$ aa this 
$ aa              # returns "this", default is function name
$ unset aa; aa    # clears any value
$ aa this is aa   # stores a new value, phrase
```

> DRY: ''D''on't ''R''epeat ''Y''ourself
A: Here is [[what DRY is not about|https://hackernoon.com/this-is-not-the-dry-you-are-looking-for-a316ed3f445f]].  backtrack to [[sayings]].  The paper caught my attention because of these remarks:

> Do not replicate a pattern. If you find a duplicated one, refactor.  Violations of this rule will immediately be pointed out by other developers as an infringement of one of the most fundamental practices of software development.  Well, let me be honest on this one. ''This approach is completely wrong.''

and:

> Shared kernels or libraries, evergrowing Util namespaces (we all have one), inheritance trees. All in the name of an irrational need to avoid writing two similar pieces of code.

In my case, it's my UtilLib in my [[bash SHELF|https://github.com/applemcg/bash]].  A quick inspection of the library suggests a few directions:

* a command line library, functions behaving like scripts,
* classes around other commands, like awk.
* others to return to their underlying commands, i.e. "duplicate code".   a good example of this is functions behaving like an //alias//, e.g:

   ```
    $ ff () { declare -f ${*:-ff}; }
```

    where aliases may be used on the command line, but not in a function or script.

See DossysReply to my question, basically restated, "I'm sure I need this, why?"







{{LastTwoWeeks}}






This little collection flies under the title: [[Where's the Input|WherestheInput]].  The main function: stdinFileArgs
 retrieves input from:

* stdin - no arguments
* File - or file arguments
* Args - if not file argument


```
stdinFileArgs () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-08-15;
    case $# in 
        0)
            report_notpipe && return 1;
            cat -
        ;;
        *)
            [[ -f $1 ]] && { 
                cat $*
            } || echo $*
        ;;
    esac
}
report_notpipe () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    [[ -p /dev/stdin ]] && return 1;
    report_usage is NOT reading a pipe
}
report_usage () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    : date: 2018-03-30;
    echo USAGE $(myname 3): $* 1>&2
}
myname () 
{ 
    : ~ [n];
    : returns name of caller OR callers caller ...;
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    echo ${FUNCNAME[${1:-1}]}
}
rotNN () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-08-15;
    stdinFileArgs $* | tr 0-9 9876543210
}
```

The latter function shows a traditional usage:   here is how you might use it:

```
test_rotNN () 
{ 
    echo 6/6/70 | rotNN;
    rotNN 6 6 70;
    ls a* > a.txt;
    rotNN a.txt
}
$ test_rotNN | grep 9
3/3/29
3 3 29
79879293
$
```
The report_not, report_usage, and myname functions challenge the [[DRY argument|WhatIsDry]].   The report_ family is so ubiquitous in my function usage, that I show these few which are used here.

In order to turn the reporting functions into assertions, the usage would look like:


```
assert_something ... || return N
```


which would require logic inversion in report_not functions.   


```
report_notsomething && return NN
```


Maybe test a few to see how it feels






At last, after a few aborted attempts, I've settled on a [[wordcount]] tool family.  

!! The requirements:

* from my Dropbox folder
* find all the `useful` files
* from just the `text source` files
* using the ''wc'' command, record the current number of lines, words, and characters for each file

Here, a //useful// file is one which:

* doesn't have a space in its name, 
* nor is a hidden file, 
* nor in a hidden directory,
* and is not an editor backup copy, 
* nor in a visible backup directory

And //text source// is a file whose suffix implies

* an emacs OrgMode file,
* a Markdown source file
* a text file (//src// or //txt //suffix)
* and explicitly is this html file: MyIdeaWarehouse

!! Usage

Any time, the `wordcount_tally` function tabulates the current data in an [[RDB|rdb]] table.   A function converts the insert_time to an insert_date, so history may be displayed by date. 

The wc command produces a total value for the character, word, and line columns.   The last tally of the day is used to report the `wordcount_changes`.  This function returns the number of words changed (i.e. added) and a (default 5 day) moving average of the changes.

Here is the up-to-date table:


```
i_date	changes	mvag
------	-------	----
190610	312	 312.0
190611	1974	 644.4
190612	662	 647.9
190614	557	 629.7
190615	555	 614.8
190616	1189	 729.6
190617	643	 712.3
190618	532	 676.2
190619	782	 697.4
```
